ble is not what we think, here the situation is reversed: what seems to be information is in fact some kind of world applying equally to all times, situations + people + places, as if we are minor characters in it, too mind to mention. Further, all scripture seems to be an account of Christ, who turns out to be the Logos or uttered word (information) on which reality derives + is based. This is quite perplexing; it is as if K-57 what we take to be map (Bible, info) is territory (world), + what we take to be territory (world) is map (infor‐ mation). This is extensively studied in Judaism regarding Torah, which is information + existed before creation; some analogic correspondence exists between Torah + world, but as to what is cause + what effect, no one can say, what is said however that even the creator cannot act contrary to Torah, + consults it is Torah ontologically prior then, to God? Does even God arise out of + on the basis of information? Clearly this infor‐ mation is somehow sentient + self-generating It is not, then, information as we normally construe the term. In my opinion \"Logos\" is the best term for this + implies \"plan\" - + at least some of this apparently living information - which is here, not there - amounts to instruc tions with the absolute power to compel reality into complying to what may be an intelligible templa the I which that t has its relation to reality that which the geometric form \"circle\" has to all actual circles. Suppose the laws that govern the universe are in their final form - ontologically speaking a body of coherent instructions in the form of information? (v. p. K-81 Christ undermines Torah's arbitrary body o K-38 the laws - all natural laws - may Then be an arbitrary system that only one possibility out of X is number of differing systems, + arise from something that thinks them, + thinks them initially as this infor‐ mation. Lastly, like the Tao that which thinks this info - formulated it does not exist. The info arises ex nihilo; it has no cause. Information, then, is the final hierarchical order of that which is. (v. p K-81) (+ this Christ combats.) If I had to make a guess I would say that the physical, sensible universe is a medium by, in or on which some mind that does not exist + yet thinks processes its own thoughts e.g. stores its thoughts for retrieval) in its effort to be purely, ab‐ It is solutely + totally self-aware reasoning, + reasoning about itself, as the reasoning cumulatively progresse (unfolds) change takes place in our universe, so that this mind can apprehend the history or corpus of what it has thought about itself. our universe, then, contains this mind's self-knowledge expressed as information, hence our universe is vital to this mind for inon + through our universe this mind remembers what it has up to now understood s K-59 since the topic of the Bible is Christ as Logos, I infer that Christ is this mind, since the Bible is an analog to the total situation in some kind of compressed short hand form, in which each letter is - or is like - a whole sub-world, only this mind - Christ - can read the Bible actually. + Christ is an abstraction; in a certain sense he does not exist but is This is not normally only conceptual something we think of as real; we view this as a category - + indeed it is! Thus Christ, as with any eidos - all eide as such - is recovered through anamnesis, but it is anamnesis dealing with your not own nature. Yet, paradoxically, it is your own nature; it is a nature on which you are based, which either you participate in or it participates in you; you are just one of many instantiatings that all together are Christ (but Christ is more than the sum of these instant. ratings; it (Christ) is only imperfectly instantiated in each + in fact all its particulars, The human faculty by which he as eides is apprehended is a rational one, but \"recovering\" such a different nature (yours as his) + world (abstract) as to seem supernatural, + yet I